AGI - Nuclear threats in the world - from Ukraine to Indo-Pacific - are multiplying. It is a result of poor historical memory, of the impor tant of dangerous partitions, but also of the disinvolvement with which some nuclear powers > resort to an undesirable and bellicist rhetoric ventilating the use of atomic devices. And all this "is inadmissible" >, deplores the President of the Republic Sergio Mattarella>.
<h2> The appeal by Hiroshima</h2>
Once in Hiroshima, the last stop of his first official visit to Japan, the head of the state chooses an emblematic place of history - the headquarters of Nihon Hidankyo>, the association of survivors to the nuclear bombs of Hiroshima and Nagasaki - to launch a sharp appeal that goes beyond the borders of the Russian-Ukraine crisis: "that no other people, than any other country, must face similar tragedies, never again!"
After deposing a crown of flowers to the memorial, with the mayor of the city, Kazumi Matsui>, Mattarella gathered together with the Italian delegation to the <em> "flamma della Pace"</em>, which burns on a stone brazier to remember the commitment to destroy all the arsenals on our planet.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> A message of memory and hope</h2>
A monument of great symbolic power preceded the words, equally powerful, pronounced after visiting the Museum of Peace and handed the president of Nihon Hidankyo> and a <em>hibahusha</em> (survived) to the 1945 nuclear attacks. "Dear hibahusha, thank you for your commitment to keep your memory alive, your teaching is a message of hope," the president began.
Mattarella reiterated: "The horror you have experienced must remain unique, tragic, divided into history, an irreversible concealment in the path of Humanity so that the threshold of nuclear annihilation is no longer crossed. "
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2>Condemnation of warlike rhetoric
Mattarella urged us not to repeat the mistakes of the past and not to be enchanted by countries which, with their fire rhetoric and the forearms, show that they have not learned from history. He made two precise references: the Russian &nbsp;Federation>, which with "irresponsible rhetoric of conflict" instilled "the unacceptable idea that nuclear devices can be ordinary instruments"; North Korea, which continues its nuclear tests, "an unforgivable attitude in this area of the world that has so suffered".
The threats to recourse to nuclear devices "are pronounced with disturbing recklessness," he said, adding that "the destinies of humanity are at stake".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> Italy's commitment
Italy, Mattarella, "condemns these dangerous drifts firmly", believes in multilateralism and strategic dialogue that "here he has avoided a new nuclear Holocaust". The Italian position is a conviction for any use of nuclear war and continues to work for the full implementation of Article VI of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty. "A nuclear war cannot be won by anyone and must never be fought," he warned.
Mattarella stressed the consolidation of the partnership between Italy and Japan, countries which, after devastating totalitarian experiences, embraced the values of democracy and free market. "Rome and Tokyo, resurfaced by the horrors of the last century, can do their part to prevent other horrors," he observed.
Finally, he hoped that the <em>hibahusha</em> of all conflicts continue to nourish the collective memory so that "the future generations do not fall into the illusion that the past is a distant shadow, devoid of teaching".
<h2> Japan's latest commitment
Tomorrow President Mattarella will visit the Shinto shrine Itsukushima, before returning to Tokyo and taking off to Rome.
